critique: This document is an executive order by Franklin D. Roosevelt approving a code of fair competition for the Paper and Pulp Industry under the National Industrial Recovery Act of 1933. It reflects a strong interventionist approach to economic regulation, typical of the New Deal era. The order also touches on labor standards by addressing minimum wage, indicating a concern for social welfare. There is no direct impact on immigration, executive power, federalism, national security, or social inclusion axes based on the text provided. The ideological tilt is clearly liberal given the context of the New Deal and the interventionist policies.
